article.description:
Richard Hamilton scored 23 points and
Chauncey Billups added 15 as the Detroit Pistons routed the Memphis
Grizzlies 109-86 Friday night.
article.headline: Hamilton sparks early Pistons' run in victory
article.linkText: Hamilton, Pistons put away Grizzlies early
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. -- The Detroit Pistons know they are going to eventually lose a game.
Hamilton

They are just enjoying delaying the inevitable as long as possible. The Pistons routed the Memphis Grizzlies 109-86 Friday night to move to 2-0 after going 8-0 in the exhibition season. "We were playing well in the preseason and we really wanted to win these first two home games before we go out west,'' said Richard Hamilton, who led Detroit with 23 points. "We were focused tonight and we really played well.'' Detroit took Memphis out of its run-and-gun style right from the opening tip. "They were the aggressors on both ends of the floor, and we never challenged them,'' Grizzlies coach Sidney Lowe said. "Obviously, we aren't ready to play with a hardworking team like that. They do what they are supposed to do, and we just weren't physical enough for them.'' Chauncey Billups added 15 points for Detroit, which also got 13 points from Zeljko Rebraca and eight points and 14 rebounds from Ben Wallace. "This was a very good team effort,'' Michael Curry said. "We wanted to take them out of their tempo by going inside and making the Grizzlies work for their shots, and we were able to do that.'' Pau Gasol and Drew Gooden led Memphis with 21 points each. "I just don't understand this,'' Gasol said. "We've played two good teams, but it is hard for me to accept these losses. We've got good players, but our defense just isn't real good.'' Memphis rookie Gordan Giricek, who scored 29 against Dallas in his NBA debut, had just six against Detroit. Four of the points came from the free-throw line, including two technical foul shots. "I saw in yesterday's paper that he had 29 -- I'm sure everyone in the league saw it,'' Hamilton said. "I spent a lot of time watching tape to make sure he didn't do that to me.'' The Pistons took control with a 17-2 first-quarter run. Hamilton had nine of the points, helping Detroit to a 31-18 lead after one quarter. "Getting off to a good start is always going to be a key for us, and that depends on our defensive effort,'' Pistons coach Rick Carlisle said. "Tonight, that was really good and it let us play from ahead. If you look at the stats, teams do a lot better when they get ahead.'' Detroit kept up the pressure in the second period, leading by as many as 24 en route to a 54-34 halftime lead. Hamilton had 12 for Detroit, while Gasol had 16 for Memphis. "Anytime you get down by 24 points, it's going to be tough to come back in this league,'' Jason Williams said. "No good team is going to let you come back from 20 down and win in this league.'' Memphis rallied midway through the third quarter, going on a 9-2 run that included two 3-pointers by Williams. But the Grizzlies still trailed 63-47 when it ended. The Pistons had the margin back to 23 at 80-57 by period's end, and were never threatened in the fourth. Detroit now leaves on a five-game West Coast trip, while the Grizzlies play two in a row at home starting Saturday against Sacramento. Game notes
There was a large contingent of Turkish fans in the Palace's upper deck, and they spent much of the second half chanting and singing in honor of Pistons rookie Mehmet Okur. Okur made his NBA debut with 8:07 to play and finished with six points and three rebounds. ... Detroit coach Rick Carlisle and Billups both picked up third-quarter technicals. Carlisle has technicals in each of Detroit's first two games. ... All 12 Pistons scored. ... The Pistons own Memphis' 2003 first-round pick, unless it is the No. 1 choice.
